commit.message:
Build system: Fix failure to correctly link to zlib (#32)

Checking for the header is NOT sufficient when utilizing its shared
library symbols. Look it up with pkg-config explicitly, and explicitly
add it to ensure that at runtime, libppd has its own DT_NEEDED
dependency on libz.so; if libppd successfully links at all -- not a
given, if -Wl,-no-undefined is used -- then it *may* transitively get
libz.so from its recursive dependencies, but this is no guarantee at
all.

Fixes failure to build discovered at https://bugs.gentoo.org/920273

commit.message:
ppdCreatePPDFromIPP2(): Also check for "pwg-raster-document-type-supported"

If the printer supports printing input in PWG Raster format, it should
not only tell that it accepts PWG Raster in
"document-format-supported" but also provide the attributes with the
specifications of what raster formats are exactly supported, and here
not only resolutions via "pwg-raster-document-resolution-supported"
but also color spaces and depths via
"pwg-raster-document-type-supported". If one of these two attributes
is missing, we disconsider PWG Raster.

See also the discussion in

https://github.com/OpenPrinting/cups/pull/890

Thanks Zdenek Dohnal and Michael Sweet.

ppd-generator.c: Check for required attributes when choosing standard (#40)

Check for PCLm and PWG attributes which we require during PPD
generation. This is not complaint with some driverless standards,
because they require more attributes, but it lets us use models which
don't exactly follow standards.

commit.message:
ppd-generator.c: Check for `urf-supported` if we found `image/urf` (#39)

Some devices has AirPrint disabled by default/admins has disabled it,
but the device reports `image/urf` in `document-format-supported`, but
provides no `urf-supported` attribute, which breaks PPD generation.

We should check for `urf-supported` once we found `image/urf`, so in
case the device is missing `urf-supported` and provides other driverless
standard, the other standard is used for PPD generation.

Fixes [Fedora issue](https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=2263053)

commit.message:
Added support for libcups3 (libcups of CUPS 3.x) (#27)

With these changes libppd can be built either with libcups2
(libcups of CUPS 2.x) or libcups3 (libcups of CUPS 3.x).

    NOTE: Any further development on the code has to be done using the
    API of libcups3, and for libcups2 support any additional
    conversion has to get defined in cupsfilters/libcups2-private.h
    (if C code is needed for the conversion, it goes into
    cupsfilters/libcups2.c).

The actual code is now fully converted to the API of libcups3. To
allow building it with libcups2 and to avoid having it full lot of "#ifdef
HAVE_LIBCUPS2" conditionals, we have added the header file
libcups2-private.h file, which gets only applied (by "#ifdef
HAVE_LIBCUPS2") when we build with libcups2.

It converts the code to the libcups2 API by

- Applying "#define ..." macro definitions for all renamings of
  functions, data types, and constants

- Converting the "cupsCreateTempFd(NULL, NULL, buffer, bufsize)" calls
  to "cupsTempFd(buffer, bufsize)" calls (new function has more
  arguments).

- Converting the "cupsCreateTempFile(NULL, NULL, buffer, bufsize)" calls
  to "cupsTempFile2(buffer, bufsize)" calls (new function has more
  arguments).

- Introducing the type "cups_len_t", as "int" for libcups2 and
  "size_t" for libcups3. In some functions there are parameters which
  make a hard switch from "int" to "size_t" with the transition to
  libcups3. For those we use this type.

- Also introducing "cups_bool_t" as "int" for libcups2 and "bool" for
  libcups3, for functions where parameters which were of type "int"
  got passed to "bool".

We also add the file libcups2.c for implementing the functions
"cupsLangGetName()" and "cupsLangGetString()", newly introduced
in libcups3 as a version for libcups2.

The files ppd/language.c and ppd/language-private.h got removed and
their functionality passed into ppd/ppd-cache.c and ppd/libcups2.c, as
there are no other files in the library using it.

In ppd/ppd-generator.c introduced data type "_ppd_size_t" to replace
the identical "cups_size_t" type which only exists in libcups2, this way
we can have the code identical for both libcups versions.

At some places we simply use casts to "(int)"instead of using the
"cups_len_t" an "cups_bool_t" types.

In ppd/ppdc-catalog.cxx we have calls of "cupsFileWrite()" which returned
the written number of bytes as "int" value. In libcups3 the function
returns success or failure as "bool". Here we had no other solution than
using "#ifdef HAVE_LIBCUPS2" conditionals.

We have a libcups3-related change in the public API header files, here
"cups_page_header2_t" got renamed into "cups_page_header_t". Due to
the fact that libcups2-private.h gets HAVE_LIBCUPS2 from config.h, we
cannot use it in the API headers (and we also do not want all these
conversions to apply to a user's code). So we simply add a renaming
"#define ..." under "#if CUPS_VERSION_MAJOR < 3" to the affected API
headers.

In configure.ac we check for libcups3 via pkg-config first and if not
present for libcups2 via cups-config. In both cases we set all relevant
variables, as compiler/linker arguments, directories, ... and in case
of libcups2 we define HAVE_LIBCUPS2 in config.h. We also do
corrections on the CXXFLAGS, adding "-std=c++17" and "-Werror"
(if the user opts for warnings treated as errors).

In Makefile.am we do not only add the new files to the build process
but we also add the compiler flag definition for C++,
"libppd_la_CXXFLAGS", simply being a copy of "libppd_la_CFLAGS".
Without it, the header files of libcups3 are not found when compiling
C++ code. We also do corrections for the build rules of the build test program
ppd/testppd.c

commit.message: libppd 2.0.0 Release

ppdLoadAttributes(): Apply cfIEEE1284NormalizeMakeModel() to NickName

The PPD's NickName sometimes contains manufacturer and model,
sometimes only the model, not the manufacturer. And manufacturer names
can be completely missing or messy.

By using cfIEEE1284NormalizeMakeModel() we clean this up and have
clear manufacturer names, for better answers print clients and correct
application of quirk rules, especially by the ppdFilterPDFToPS()
filter function.

Improved solution for Pull Request #21.

ppd/ppd-ipp.c: Use make when constructing printer-make-model attr (#21)

We used only PPD Nickname which does not contain manufacturer in some
drivers (like Utax) when constructing printer-make-and-model IPP
attribute, and then used the attribute when matching with strings
representing manufacturers in filter functions.

This caused internal hacks for specific printer manufacturers weren't
applied, causing breakage during printing.

commit.message:
raster-interpret.c: Fix CVE-2023-4504

We didn't check for end of buffer if it looks there is an escaped
character - check for NULL terminator there and if found, return NULL
as return value and in `ptr`, because a lone backslash is not
a valid PostScript character.

Decode "JCLToPDFInterpreter" value in ppdEmitJCLPDF()

In ppdEmitJCLPDF() the "JCLToPDFInterpreter" value from the PPD file
is read out without decoding, producing broken PJL before the PDF
print data output for "classic" (non-driverless) PDF printing.

Also promoted the static function "ppd_decode()" of ppd/ppd.c into
the API function "ppdDecode()".

Fixes #24.
libppd 2.0rc2 Release
CHANGES.md: Fixed typos.

ppdFilterLoadPPD(): Actually create Raster header also for Apple/PWG Raster

Not only if the PPD's "*cupsFilter(2): ..." attributes specify CUPS
Raster as format needed from the CUPS filters but also for Apple
Raster or PWG Raster a sample header for the filter functions should
be generated.

This commit fixes the additional checks for the "cupsUrfSupported" and
"cupsPwgRasterDocumentTypeSupported" PPD attributes and now the sample
header gets created for all Raster formats.

PPD file generator: Put "*cupsSingleFile: True" into generated PPD

Fix overtaken from CUPS:

    https://github.com/OpenPrinting/cups/commit/67a8e09e7

Some printers are not able to print multiple files in one job via IPP
Everywhere. Adding the PPD keyword enables the feature on all printers
in exchange for performance degradation (there is a 1-2s pause between
printed files).

Fixes

    https://github.com/OpenPrinting/cups/issues/643

also if the PPD is generated by the driverless utility or by
cups-browsed.

Merge fixes from CUPS code

The PPD file support code from libucps was overtaken into libppd back
ing 2020, near 3 years ago:

https://openprinting.github.io/OpenPrinting-News-July-2020/#cups-filters

Even PPD files having been deprecated, there still happened a lot of
changes on the PPD support code in CUPS, some got merged into the copy
in libppd but not all.

So before the final release of libpps 2.0.0 I have looked through the
code and merged all fixes which did not make it into libppd yet.

Most are minor bug fixes, silencing warnings (especially of clang),
fixing typos in comments, coding style, ..., but there are also some
fixes for memory leaks, and even we add now some extra CUPS-specific
attributes to the PPD files we generate, to activate some of CUPS'
recently added new functionality, like providing tarnslations of
option and choice names without them being in the PPD files.

Here are some highlights:

- Add CUPS PPD attributes "*cupsLanguages: ...", "*cupsStringsURI ..."
  to generated PPDs so that CUPS loads printer-specific option
  names and translations from the printer and uses them without need
  of static translations in the PPD file.

- CUPS renames the PPD option choice name "Custom" to "_Custom" when a
  fixed choice is named as such, to distinguish from CUPS' facility
  for custom option values. Do the same when loading PPD files.

- Prevent duplicate PPD->IPP media-type name mappings

- When not specifying a media source and the page size is small
  (5x7" or smaller) do not request the photo tray but "auto" instead.

- Do not override color settings from print dialog (ColorModel) with
  print-color-mode setting.

- Make ppdFilterPSToPS() recognize "%%PageRequirements:" DSC comment.

- Correctly display "Xprinter" instead of Xerox for Xprinter devices

- Fix the job-pages-per-set value (used to apply finishings correctly)
  for duplex and N-up printing.

- Make the testppd test program also work if it is started from an
  environment with non-English locale.

ppdFilterPSToPS(): Fixed reverse output order

With PPD files for PostScript printers or for (proprietary) driver
filters requiring PostScript input (for example Brother) and where the
printer which stacks the printed paper face-up and therefpre needs
reverse output order for correct stacking ("*DefaultOutputOrder:
Reverse" in PPD) there was no output at all. ppdFilterPSToPS() turned
the PostScript input file into empty, zero-bytes output.

The empty output is due to a wrong function being used for the
output. This was most probably introduced with the conversion of the
pstops CUPS filter to the ppdFilterPSToPS() filter function. At too
many places the regular puts()/printf() got replaced by
doc_puts()/doc_printf() where actually just a fputs()/fprintf() to
outputfd had been needed.

This is corrected now and we get correct output for these PPD files
again.

Fixes #20: https://github.com/OpenPrinting/libppd/issues/20

Fixed resolution handling when converting PPDs to printer IPP attributes

When converting the PPD file into printer IPP attributes, usually for
filter functions of libcupsfilters to be used in classic CUPS filters,
the resolution was not handled correctly.

If the intended output is PWG Raster, Apple Raster, or PCLm,
specifying a resolution in the job IPP attributes or the CUPS job
options is ignored, also a default resolution specified in the PPD
file or a resolution resulting from pseudo-PostScript assigned to the
option choices in the PPD. Instead, always the first (lowest)
resolution in the list of supported resolutions for the output Raster
format is used.

Now we respect job attributes, pseudo-PostScript code, and PPD's
default resolution with priority, and fall back to the base resolution
for the output Raster format only if everything else fails.

In many cases we get higher output resolution by that.

All PPD files with "MirrorPrint" option cuased mirrored printout

If a PPD contains an option "MirrorPrint", the ppdFilterLoadPPD()
sent the option "mirror=true" to the filter functions, regardless
of the actual setting of "MirrorPrint" (which is usually "False"
by default).

This made all printouts on printers using a PPD file with a
"MirrorPrint" option coming out mirrored, with no way to counteract
this by any options or attributes.

This is fixed now by checking the setting of "MirrorPrint".

See https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/2018538
libppd 2.0rc1 Release
Makefile.am: Fixed typos

PPD generator for driverless printers: add "*LandscapeOrientation:"

In the generated PPD files add the keyword "*LandscapeOrientation:"
with the values "Plus90" or "Minus90" according to the
landscape-orientation-requested-preferred printer IPP attribute with
values "4" and "5" resp.

PPD file generator: Set default color mode when printer attrs say "auto"

With the printer reporting "print-color-mode-default=auto" in its IPP
attributes "RGB" got never set as default when for the ColorModel
option when a color choice got found for "print-color-mode", but
"Gray" was set when there was a standard monochromr choice, leadin to
color printers getting grayscale as default color mode.

Now this is fixed and always the "best" color mode chosen as default.

See https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/2014976
